The '''Bruges dialect''' ([[Dutch language|Standard Dutch]] and [[West Flemish]]: ''Brugs'') is a West Flemish dialect used in [[Bruges]]. It is rapidly declining, being replaced with what scholars call general (rural) West Flemish.{{sfnp|Hinskens|Taeldeman|2013|p=167}}{{sfnp|Vandekerckhove|2010|p=326}}{{sfnp|Taeldeman|2005|p=277}}

==Phonology==

===Consonants===
* After {{IPA|/u/}}, the sequence {{IPA|/nd/}} is realized as a velar nasal {{IPAblink|ŋ}}.{{sfnp|Hinskens|Taeldeman|2013|p=167}}
* The sequence {{IPA|/ən/}} is realized as a sequence {{IPA|[ən]}}, rather than a syllabic {{IPA|[n̩]}}.{{sfnp|Hinskens|Taeldeman|2013|p=167}}

====Realization of {{IPA|/r/}}====
According to {{Harvcoltxt|Hinskens|Taeldeman|2013}}, {{IPA|/r/}} is realized as a voiced uvular trill with little friction {{IPAblink|ʀ̝}}. In the neighbouring rural area, an alveolar {{IPAblink|r}} is used.{{sfnp|Hinskens|Taeldeman|2013|p=167}}

However, according to {{Harvcoltxt|Sebregts|2014}}, the vast majority of the speakers in Bruges realize {{IPA|/r/}} as alveolar, not uvular.{{sfnp|Sebregts|2014|p=90}}

Definitely, the most common realization of {{IPA|/r/}} is a voiced alveolar tap {{IPAblink|ɾ}}, which is used about four times more often than the second most common realization, which is a voiced alveolar trill {{IPAblink|r}}. The other alveolar realizations include: a voiceless alveolar trill {{IPAblink|r̥}}, a partially devoiced alveolar trill {{IPAblink|r̥}}, a voiceless alveolar fricative tap/trill {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɾ̞̊}} ~ {{IPA link|r̝̊}}]}}, a voiceless alveolar/postalveolar fricative {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɹ̝̊}}, {{IPA link|ɹ̠̊˔}}]}} (the least common realization), a voiced alveolar/postalveolar fricative {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɹ̝}} ~ {{IPA link|ɹ̠˔}}]}} and a voiced alveolar approximant {{IPAblink|ɹ}}.{{sfnp|Sebregts|2014|p=90}}

Among the uvular realizations, he lists a voiced uvular trill {{IPAblink|ʀ}}, a voiced uvular fricative trill {{IPAblink|ʀ̝}}, a voiced uvular fricative {{IPAblink|ʁ}} and a voiced uvular approximant {{IPAblink|ʁ̞}}, among which the uvular fricative trill is the most common realization. He also lists a central vowel (which probably means {{IPAblink|ə}}, {{IPAblink|ɐ}} or both of these) and elision of {{IPA|/r/}}, both of which are very rare.{{sfnp|Sebregts|2014|p=90}}

