* In comparison with Standard Dutch, the short front vowels underwent a chain shift, so that the standard {{IPA|/i, y, ɪ, ʏ, ɛ/}} became {{IPA|/ɪ, ʏ, ɛ, œ, æ/}}. The standard {{IPA|/u/}} was also lowered to {{IPA|/ʊ/}}, yet the standard {{IPA|/ɔ/}} was left untouched.
* Among the back vowels, {{IPA|/ʊ, ɔ, ɔː/}} are rounded, whereas {{IPA|/ɑ, ɑː/}} are unrounded.
* {{IPA|/ɪ, ʏ, ʊ/}} are near-close {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪ̟}}, {{IPA link|ʏ}}, {{IPA link|ʊ̠}}]}}; {{IPA|/ɪ/}} is fully front, whereas {{IPA|/ʊ/}} is fully back.
* {{IPA|/ʏ, ʊ, œː/}} (but not {{IPA|/œ, ɔ, ɔː/}}) are rather weakly rounded {{IPA|[ʏ̜, ʊ̜, œ̜ː]}}.
* Phonetically, {{IPA|/ɛ, ə/}} are mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɛ̝}}, {{IPA link|ə}}]}}, whereas {{IPA|/ɛː, ɛ̃ː, œ, œː, ɔ, ɔː/}} are open-mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɛː}}, ɛ̃ː, {{IPA link|œ}}, {{IPA link|œː}}, {{IPA link|ɔ}}, {{IPA link|ɔː}}]}}.
* Before {{IPA|/l/}}, {{IPA|/æ/}} is lowered and retracted to {{IPAblink|ɑ}}. This feature is typical of working class speech and is nearly extinct.{{sfnp|Hinskens|Taeldeman|2013|p=167}}{{sfnp|Vandekerckhove|2010|p=326}}

