{{Orphan|date=January 2015}}

'''Postmodern law''', and postmodern jurisprudence, relates to interpretations of the legal system using [[postmodern philosophy]] and the theories of [[postmodernism]].  It also relevant to law within the context of the [[postmodern]] era.  Since the mid-1990s Annual meetings of the [[Association of American Law Schools]] have focused on the inclusion of postmodern interpretative strategies at these meetings.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/31436150|title=Postmodern legal movements : law and jurisprudence at century's end|last=Gary.|first=Minda,|date=1995|publisher=New York University Press|isbn=0814755100|location=New York|oclc=31436150}}</ref> Postmodern interpretations of the law can involve critically considering legal inequalities connected to [[gender]], [[Class (social)|class]], [[Race (classification of humans)|race]] and [[ethnicity]] by acknowledging "diversity and multiplicity".  Critical practices connected to postmodern philosophy, such as [[critical literacy]] and [[deconstruction]], can be used as an interpretative tool to ensure that a range of different and [[Diversity (politics)|diverse]] values and norms are acknowledged or considered.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/173368722|title=Sociology of law : visions of a scholarly tradition|last=Mathieu.|first=Deflem,|date=2008|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521857253|location=Cambridge, UK|oclc=173368722}}</ref>

